# Developer Guide — working with Claude on {{PROJECT_NAME}}

The operating manual for every developer (and for Claude). Short version: **describe what you want in
plain language; Claude grounds in the knowledge base, agrees the scope with you, builds it, proves it
works, and keeps the knowledge base current.** No FRDs/tickets required.

## 1. Mental model
1. **The knowledge base is the source of truth** (`.claude/knowledgebase/` + `.claude/database/`),
   read before work and updated in the *same change* as the code — so any session resumes with full context.
2. **Every change runs one loop** (the `feature-workflow` skill): capture → ground → decide →
   implement → self-test → review → verify → sync KB → commit.
3. **Lightweight by default** — requirements come from you in chat; ceremony is added only when the work justifies it.

## 2. Do we need an FRD?
No. The value of an FRD (a captured, agreed requirement) is kept lighter:
- a dated line in the **requirements changelog** for every request;
- a one-page **`plans/<NN-name>/plan.md`** for bigger initiatives (a one-page FRD + plan combined).

Say **"write this up as a plan first"** to get the FRD feel: Claude drafts the one-pager, you approve, then build.

## 3. Two tiers
- **Tier 1 — small change (default):** describe it → Claude logs, implements, runs the gate ({{GATE}}),
  verifies for real, updates the KB, commits. No plan folder.
- **Tier 2 — feature/initiative:** discuss first, then the plan lifecycle (the folder = the status):
  ```
  DISCUSS ─▶ plan.md ─▶ plans/upcoming/ ─▶ plans/inprogress/ (+tasks.md) ─▶ plans/done/
  ```
  Two gates Claude asks at: (1) "shall I write this up as a plan?" (2) "shall I move it to in-progress
  and start?". On completion, durable knowledge is folded into the KB and the folder moves to `done/`.

## 4. How to phrase a request
Describe the **problem and the outcome**, not the implementation. Claude asks clarifying questions,
proposes an approach (drafts the plan for Tier 2), decides reversible details itself, and only asks you
on irreversible/costly/scope-expanding/conflicting/secret-needing choices.

## 5. Under the hood (ask by name if you want)
- **Skills**: `feature-workflow`, `qa-review`{{, db-change, browser-verify, find-skills}} — Claude uses these; you can request them.
- **Review agents**: `security-reviewer`, `quality-reviewer`, `professional-qa` — "run a full QA pass" spawns them.
- **Hooks**: secret/credential writes blocked automatically; {{project pitfall}} flagged.

## 6. The "done" gate
Type-check + build clean · {{GATE}} all-PASS · the behaviour verified for real · KB updated in the same change.
Claude won't claim done on green tests alone.

## 7. Git & shipping
Commit per slice on {{DEFAULT_BRANCH}} as {{GIT_IDENTITY}}; **push only when asked**; no auto-PRs;
never commit secrets; staged paths are checked before commit.

## 8. CLI vs other surfaces
Drive it anywhere, but the **terminal (Claude Code CLI)** is where hooks, per-project permissions, and
the custom agents/skills are *enforced* (see `ai-workflow-kit/WHY-TERMINAL.md`). Run from the repo root.

## 9. Cheat sheet
| You want to… | Say… |
|---|---|
| Make a small change | just describe it |
| Spec something bigger | "write this up as a plan" |
| Start a planned feature | "move it to in-progress and build it" |
| Get a review/QA pass | "run a full QA pass before we ship" |
| Verify a UI | "browser-verify the X screen" |
| Ship it | "push it" |
| Know the state | "what's the status?" |
